@NODE "mail_11" " RE: Gadgets & Mouse "
From: David McMinn <dave@...>
Date: 10-15-01 11:03:47
Subject: @{b}RE: Gadgets & Mouse@{ub}

Hi Sven,

> Is use the IDCMP_HELPxxx event for my program, but as this only gives a
> message after a special time, it is not usable for a
> mouse-over-gadget-checking...

You mean IDCMP_GADGETHELP? Well, if that's not suitable, I guess you'd need to 
manually check gadgets yourself.

If you check on each IDCMP_MOUSEMOVE event, you should be able to check the 
gadgets as soon as the mouse is moved. I'm not sure what the fastest way of 
doing the checks are though, but you'd want it really fast or your program 
would be sluggish.

I guess you could partition your gadgets up into different areas, e.g. gadgets 
in the topleft, topright, bottomleft and bottomright corners of your window. 
Then, depending on where the mouse position is, you only need to check one of 
those four areas.

To check each area, I guess you could just have some arrays with the top, 
left, width and height of each gadget which you could compare against the 
mouse pointer.

