OK, using the MUILabel command:-

MUILabel Obj No,"Label Text",#MUIO_Label_Centered

will centre a label in the window (I'm not sure about how it would perform in a
HGroup, though). However, there seems to be a bug with the MUILabel command
which will stop the GUI resizing if you use it. To get around this, create your
own instead:-

MUINewObject obj
no,"Text.mui",#MUIA_Frame,#MUIV_Frame_String,#MUIA_Text_Contents,
&gdisp$,#MUIA_Background,#MUII_TextBack

(all on one line) will create a text object with a string frame around it,
containt the text defined in gdisp$ using the standard background colour. You
can apply other standard MUI flags to this object (see the MUI Area doc), or
you can parse text in place with the use of control characters. So, for
example, using the command:-

gdisp$=Chr$(27)+"c"+your text

BEFORE you create the object will centre the text. Other supported control codes
are listed in the MUI_Text doc. (Chr$(27) is Esc), which allows preparsing.

You can later change the contents of the Text object, if you wish, with:-

gdisp$="Whatever you want - including formatting codes"
MUISet obj No,#MUIA_Text_Contents,&gdisp$

Hope this helps.

